snippet.textDisplay:
BDG, you can check to see if the fire extinguisher is still good by looking at the pressure gauge on it, if it has one. If the arrow is pointing to a green section that means that it still has adequate pressure and should still work. They are designed to sit for long periods of time and to rarely be used but some do have expiration dates. If you can't be sure about its functionality it's definitely a good idea to get a new one. They are never a bad thing to have around and are relatively inexpensive. Especially when weighed against the things you own that might go up in flames.

Also, you might make sure that it is able to extinguish the fires you'll most likely have in the area where you keep it. For instance, some are designed to be used on grease fires while others won't work on electric fires without acting as a medium that transfers the electricity back to it and ultimately you. Not many are like that but some are, especially older ones. Just a heads up. I don't want to see you lose your life, apartment, or cats because of a poor choice in fire extinguisher.

The key thing about a fire extinguisher use is that you should never opt to use one on a fire that is already out of control. You only use them on small fires before they get out of hand. If it's past the point where a small extinguisher can help, then run to safety, pull the fire alarm, and be careful. Also, call 911. The fire alarm doesn't always immediately notify the fire department and they might have further questions even if it does. This is all general advice that I do not recommend anyone follow without using your own best judgement and/or checking with your local fire code and safety guidelines. Don't rely on an internet comment to tell you everything you need to know about fire safety. I'm just speaking from my experience and yours may vary.
